1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
 (audience laughing)

2
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:10,920
 - Hey porch, join us as we read God's word together.

3
00:00:10,920 --> 00:00:17,920
 From the book of 2 Timothy chapter three,

4
00:00:17,920 --> 00:00:19,280
 verses one through nine.

5
00:00:19,280 --> 00:00:25,480
 But understand this, that in the last days,

6
00:00:25,480 --> 00:00:27,520
 there will come times of difficulty.

7
00:00:29,240 --> 00:00:31,600
 For people will be lovers of self,

8
00:00:31,600 --> 00:00:36,600
 lovers of money, proud, arrogant, abusive,

9
00:00:36,600 --> 00:00:41,380
 disobedient to their parents, ungrateful, unholy.

10
00:00:41,380 --> 00:00:53,800
 Heartless, unappeasable, slanderous,

11
00:00:53,800 --> 00:00:56,640
 without self-control, brutal,

12
00:00:58,640 --> 00:01:00,080
 and not loving good.

13
00:01:00,080 --> 00:01:10,680
 Treacherous, reckless, swollen with conceit,

14
00:01:10,680 --> 00:01:13,900
 lovers of pleasure rather than lovers of God.

15
00:01:13,900 --> 00:01:22,920
 Having the appearance of Godliness, but denying

16
00:01:25,720 --> 00:01:28,700
 its power, avoid such people.

17
00:01:28,700 --> 00:01:36,440
 For among them are those who creep into households

18
00:01:36,440 --> 00:01:41,440
 and capture weak women, burdened with sin and led astray.

19
00:01:41,440 --> 00:01:48,080
 Always learning and never able to arrive

20
00:01:48,080 --> 00:01:52,240
 at a knowledge of truth, just as Janus and Jambres

21
00:01:52,240 --> 00:01:57,240
 opposed Moses, so these men also opposed the truth.

22
00:01:57,240 --> 00:02:03,280
 Men corrupted in mind and disqualified regarding the faith.

23
00:02:03,280 --> 00:02:11,180
 But they will not get very far for their folly

24
00:02:11,180 --> 00:02:15,280
 will be plain to all, as was that of those two men.

25
00:02:15,280 --> 00:02:19,960
 Now the fourth message in the series, 2 Timothy.

26
00:02:21,240 --> 00:02:24,200
 - Amazing, amazing, amazing.

27
00:02:24,200 --> 00:02:26,440
 Porch, how are we doing tonight?

28
00:02:26,440 --> 00:02:27,280
 We doing okay?

29
00:02:27,280 --> 00:02:28,240
 It's great to see you.

30
00:02:28,240 --> 00:02:30,680
 So glad you're here in the room.

31
00:02:30,680 --> 00:02:34,120
 I am eager to get into this text,

32
00:02:34,120 --> 00:02:38,680
 but it is always such a joy to get together in this space

33
00:02:38,680 --> 00:02:40,260
 and to have you here with us,

34
00:02:40,260 --> 00:02:43,080
 but not just those of you that are here in this room with us

35
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:44,440
 and those of you that are walking in right now,

36
00:02:44,440 --> 00:02:46,140
 welcome, so great to have you,

37
00:02:46,140 --> 00:02:49,160
 but also all of those who are tuning in,

38
00:02:49,160 --> 00:02:53,240
 just wherever it is, they might be watching this message.

39
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:54,960
 Like people are watching with us tonight,

40
00:02:54,960 --> 00:02:56,640
 but people will be watching this in the future.

41
00:02:56,640 --> 00:02:58,960
 And so we're just grateful that you would give up

42
00:02:58,960 --> 00:03:01,640
 the time that you are to be a part of what God is doing

43
00:03:01,640 --> 00:03:03,200
 here at the porch.

44
00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:05,640
 Special shout out to Porch Life, Wheaton, Scottsdale,

45
00:03:05,640 --> 00:03:07,400
 and Fort Worth.

46
00:03:07,400 --> 00:03:10,440
 All right, well, hey, just a few months ago,

47
00:03:10,440 --> 00:03:15,440
 our son Cash finally started crawling around our house

48
00:03:15,440 --> 00:03:19,060
 and we were elated when he started to do it

49
00:03:19,060 --> 00:03:22,040
 because we had been anticipating this moment

50
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:24,520
 when he would begin to inch around.

51
00:03:24,520 --> 00:03:26,440
 You see, he was kind of a late bloomer to the whole thing.

52
00:03:26,440 --> 00:03:27,640
 We didn't know if it was just because

53
00:03:27,640 --> 00:03:29,600
 he was content to be carried around,

54
00:03:29,600 --> 00:03:30,540
 I'd be down for that,

55
00:03:30,540 --> 00:03:32,640
 or it was just because his belly was so big

56
00:03:32,640 --> 00:03:35,520
 that he actually couldn't get himself up off the ground.

57
00:03:35,520 --> 00:03:38,020
 But eventually he started making some headway,

58
00:03:38,020 --> 00:03:40,360
 navigating around our house.

59
00:03:40,360 --> 00:03:42,480
 And as he did so,

60
00:03:42,480 --> 00:03:46,400
 we realized that there was a whole new world set before him,

61
00:03:46,400 --> 00:03:47,220
 but not just him,

62
00:03:47,220 --> 00:03:49,480
 there was a whole new way in which we were seeing

63
00:03:49,480 --> 00:03:50,760
 our world as well.

64
00:03:50,760 --> 00:03:53,500
 Because as soon as he started crawling around our home,

65
00:03:53,500 --> 00:03:55,520
 not only was he seeing the world in a new way,

66
00:03:55,520 --> 00:03:56,400
 we were too.

67
00:03:56,400 --> 00:03:58,280
 Where we once thought our home was this

68
00:03:58,280 --> 00:04:01,200
 perfect little starter set for a family of three,

69
00:04:01,200 --> 00:04:02,920
 new to the Dallas area.

70
00:04:02,920 --> 00:04:06,020
 Now we realized our house was a virtual death trap.

71
00:04:06,020 --> 00:04:12,220
 Like he had exposed every baby-proofing deficiency

72
00:04:12,220 --> 00:04:16,880
 and every danger that our home happened to present.

73
00:04:16,880 --> 00:04:18,280
 You see, we had done some of the things,

74
00:04:18,280 --> 00:04:21,840
 we're not unwise or naive parents.

75
00:04:21,840 --> 00:04:22,880
 Like we had done some research

76
00:04:22,880 --> 00:04:24,400
 and begun to kind of set up our home

77
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:26,360
 to prepare for a child that might move about.

78
00:04:26,360 --> 00:04:28,640
 But he was exposing things the likes of which

79
00:04:28,640 --> 00:04:30,400
 we had never before even thought.

80
00:04:30,400 --> 00:04:32,640
 Like he would be crawling across the ground

81
00:04:32,640 --> 00:04:34,080
 and because he's a hungry little boy,

82
00:04:34,080 --> 00:04:35,120
 he'd find a leaf that had blown in

83
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:36,080
 and he'd pop it into his mouth.

84
00:04:36,080 --> 00:04:37,960
 Man, you probably shouldn't eat that thing.

85
00:04:37,960 --> 00:04:40,200
 Or he would pull himself up and we were like,

86
00:04:40,200 --> 00:04:41,600
 oh my gosh, he's pulling himself up

87
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:43,400
 until he pulled himself up on the toilet

88
00:04:43,400 --> 00:04:45,040
 and he started to drink out of the bowl.

89
00:04:45,040 --> 00:04:46,000
 That's not good.

90
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:47,560
 You know, or he decided, man,

91
00:04:47,560 --> 00:04:50,160
 I'm gonna just start swinging open cabinets

92
00:04:50,160 --> 00:04:51,100
 but not moving my hand

93
00:04:51,100 --> 00:04:53,820
 and just closing my hand in there as well.

94
00:04:53,820 --> 00:04:56,080
 We also saw that he would slobber all over his hands

95
00:04:56,080 --> 00:04:57,520
 and then he would slap electric outlets.

96
00:04:57,520 --> 00:04:59,320
 That seems like a really bad idea.

97
00:04:59,320 --> 00:05:01,840
 Or he made his way into our bathroom and we're getting ready

98
00:05:01,840 --> 00:05:03,880
 and he finds our medicine cabinet

99
00:05:03,880 --> 00:05:05,320
 and he starts pulling out pill bottles

100
00:05:05,320 --> 00:05:06,300
 and shaking them like rattles.

101
00:05:06,300 --> 00:05:07,280
 And it's like, that's not a good idea

102
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:09,400
 'cause that's not a baby toy in the slightest.

103
00:05:09,400 --> 00:05:13,080
 He had exposed that our home was so much more dangerous

104
00:05:13,080 --> 00:05:14,400
 than we expected.

105
00:05:15,400 --> 00:05:17,160
 And so now our home isn't just baby-proofed,

106
00:05:17,160 --> 00:05:18,120
 it's Kylan-proofed.

107
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:20,240
 Every electric outlet is covered.

108
00:05:20,240 --> 00:05:22,360
 Every single cabinet is locked.

109
00:05:22,360 --> 00:05:25,680
 Every single sharp edge has a bumper on it.

110
00:05:25,680 --> 00:05:29,440
 It is now set up for his protection.

111
00:05:29,440 --> 00:05:33,280
 And the reason why is he had exposed to us some dangers

112
00:05:33,280 --> 00:05:37,820
 that we didn't expect to be true of that space.

113
00:05:37,820 --> 00:05:39,680
 Now, why do I tell you that?

114
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:42,860
 Because for many of you, if you look at your life,

115
00:05:42,860 --> 00:05:45,060
 like we looked at our home, you look at it and you think,

116
00:05:45,060 --> 00:05:47,120
 man, this is really well set up.

117
00:05:47,120 --> 00:05:49,360
 Like it's accommodating for my comfort

118
00:05:49,360 --> 00:05:51,820
 and it's relatively predictable

119
00:05:51,820 --> 00:05:54,000
 and it's set up for my success.

120
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:57,520
 Like I feel like I've prepared it the way that I like.

121
00:05:57,520 --> 00:06:00,280
 And yet, for lack of a better word,

122
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:01,760
 what you're saying is that you just feel

123
00:06:01,760 --> 00:06:04,760
 like your world is safe,

124
00:06:04,760 --> 00:06:07,720
 which isn't an uncommon experience for you.

125
00:06:07,720 --> 00:06:10,760
 It's actually a common sort of interpretation

126
00:06:10,760 --> 00:06:12,880
 that people have all across the world.

127
00:06:12,880 --> 00:06:15,220
 I thought this was really interesting.

128
00:06:15,220 --> 00:06:20,220
 Gallup's 2025 global safety report showed that 73%,

129
00:06:20,220 --> 00:06:24,140
 that's three quarters of adults worldwide,

130
00:06:24,140 --> 00:06:27,000
 feel safe when walking alone at night.

131
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:28,740
 Do you feel safe walking alone at night?

132
00:06:28,740 --> 00:06:30,740
 Three quarters of the world would say

133
00:06:30,740 --> 00:06:33,500
 that they do feel safe when walking at night.

134
00:06:33,500 --> 00:06:35,180
 And the reason this is so significant

135
00:06:35,180 --> 00:06:37,620
 is because this is the highest mark

136
00:06:37,620 --> 00:06:39,940
 that this annual survey has ever reported

137
00:06:39,940 --> 00:06:42,300
 over the course of the last 20 years.

138
00:06:42,300 --> 00:06:46,220
 It's crazy to think that people look at their life

139
00:06:46,220 --> 00:06:47,660
 and they think, man, I feel so safe,

140
00:06:47,660 --> 00:06:49,680
 which begged for me the question, why is that?

141
00:06:49,680 --> 00:06:52,620
 Like, why is it that people look at their world

142
00:06:52,620 --> 00:06:55,220
 and think it is safe to exist within?

143
00:06:55,220 --> 00:06:57,060
 And there's a lot that we could say,

144
00:06:57,060 --> 00:06:58,260
 but if you read through the research,

145
00:06:58,260 --> 00:07:00,860
 really what it boils down to is they feel safe,

146
00:07:00,860 --> 00:07:03,300
 secure within the structures

147
00:07:03,300 --> 00:07:06,460
 and satisfaction of their communities.

148
00:07:06,460 --> 00:07:09,720
 They look at the people that they rub shoulders with

149
00:07:09,720 --> 00:07:10,740
 day in and day out,

150
00:07:10,740 --> 00:07:14,220
 those that they see at the water cooler in the office,

151
00:07:14,220 --> 00:07:17,660
 the friends that they have when they go out on the weekends

152
00:07:17,660 --> 00:07:18,860
 or the neighbors they pass by

153
00:07:18,860 --> 00:07:20,020
 when they're walking their dogs.

154
00:07:20,020 --> 00:07:23,340
 And they think, man, this is a safe environment

155
00:07:23,340 --> 00:07:25,180
 for me to dwell within.

156
00:07:25,180 --> 00:07:27,520
 They don't see any suspect of danger at all.

157
00:07:27,520 --> 00:07:30,060
 But what if I told you that like our home,

158
00:07:30,060 --> 00:07:31,960
 your world isn't as safe as you think?

159
00:07:31,960 --> 00:07:36,460
 What if I told you the people and the places

160
00:07:36,460 --> 00:07:38,340
 that you feel safest in,

161
00:07:38,340 --> 00:07:41,980
 your community is actually more dangerous

162
00:07:41,980 --> 00:07:43,140
 than you would expect?

163
00:07:43,140 --> 00:07:46,740
 Well, that's exactly what the apostle Paul

164
00:07:46,740 --> 00:07:48,340
 wants to talk to us about tonight

165
00:07:48,340 --> 00:07:51,980
 as we continue in his letter to his protege Timothy.

166
00:07:51,980 --> 00:07:53,420
 If you have a Bible, you can grab it.

167
00:07:53,420 --> 00:07:57,060
 We're going to be in 2 Timothy chapter three.

168
00:07:57,060 --> 00:07:57,940
 And as you're turning there,

169
00:07:57,940 --> 00:07:59,820
 I'm just going to catch you up because I don't know,

170
00:07:59,820 --> 00:08:01,380
 maybe you're here for the very first time

171
00:08:01,380 --> 00:08:03,260
 and you're sort of injecting yourself

172
00:08:03,260 --> 00:08:04,940
 into the middle of this series,

173
00:08:04,940 --> 00:08:06,220
 like you would the middle of a movie.

174
00:08:06,220 --> 00:08:08,140
 And so some background would be helpful for you.

175
00:08:08,140 --> 00:08:10,860
 Just so you can understand what we've been talking about.

176
00:08:10,860 --> 00:08:14,160
 What do you have to understand is this is Paul's final letter

177
00:08:14,160 --> 00:08:16,300
 to his son in the faith,

178
00:08:16,300 --> 00:08:19,380
 the guy that he has invested his life pouring into

179
00:08:19,380 --> 00:08:21,520
 and raising up this young man named Timothy.

180
00:08:21,520 --> 00:08:22,740
 Timothy is like you.

181
00:08:22,740 --> 00:08:27,280
 He's a young leader in a materialistic sort of culture,

182
00:08:27,280 --> 00:08:31,020
 one where society really commends success.

183
00:08:31,020 --> 00:08:32,780
 And Paul is writing to him and he's telling him,

184
00:08:32,780 --> 00:08:36,200
 hey, there are some attitudes that you need to adopt

185
00:08:36,200 --> 00:08:37,900
 as you walk within this world.

186
00:08:37,900 --> 00:08:40,700
 That's what the first chapter and a half was about.

187
00:08:40,700 --> 00:08:42,900
 And then when you get into the latter half of chapter two,

188
00:08:42,900 --> 00:08:45,860
 he starts to tell him about all these activities

189
00:08:45,860 --> 00:08:47,260
 that you need to begin to adopt as well.

190
00:08:47,260 --> 00:08:50,060
 He's going to pick those up as we continue next week.

191
00:08:50,060 --> 00:08:53,400
 But as we turn the corner into chapter three,

192
00:08:53,400 --> 00:08:55,540
 what Paul's actually going to do is he's going to turn

193
00:08:55,540 --> 00:08:57,340
 Timothy's attention away from himself

194
00:08:57,340 --> 00:09:00,580
 and he's going to turn it onto the world around him.

195
00:09:00,580 --> 00:09:03,900
 He wants to prepare Timothy for what he's to face

196
00:09:03,900 --> 00:09:06,620
 in the midst of this very secularized society.

197
00:09:06,620 --> 00:09:08,460
 For lack of a better term, what he's going to do

198
00:09:08,460 --> 00:09:10,420
 for Timothy is what my coaches would do

199
00:09:10,420 --> 00:09:11,740
 when I played high school football.

200
00:09:11,740 --> 00:09:14,820
 He's going to hand Timothy a scouting report.

201
00:09:14,820 --> 00:09:16,700
 Why would my coaches do that for me?

202
00:09:16,700 --> 00:09:19,580
 Because they wanted to set me up for success.

203
00:09:19,580 --> 00:09:22,980
 They wanted to prepare me for that six foot,

204
00:09:22,980 --> 00:09:26,060
 four inch, 300 pound plus East Texas,

205
00:09:26,060 --> 00:09:30,620
 you know, farm raised, corn fed sort of young boy.

206
00:09:30,620 --> 00:09:32,340
 Like that's what they were trying to get me ready for.

207
00:09:32,340 --> 00:09:34,620
 They knew, hey, you're going to need all the help

208
00:09:34,620 --> 00:09:37,780
 you can get because that guy actually,

209
00:09:37,780 --> 00:09:41,660
 he outmatches you in some pretty material kind of ways.

210
00:09:41,660 --> 00:09:43,220
 Paul's looking at Timothy and he's like, hey,

211
00:09:43,220 --> 00:09:45,300
 the world you're walking into is one

212
00:09:45,300 --> 00:09:48,260
 that is filled with danger and I want to prepare you

213
00:09:48,260 --> 00:09:49,100
 as well as I can.

214
00:09:49,100 --> 00:09:51,620
 I want to set you up for success.

215
00:09:51,620 --> 00:09:55,500
 I need you to understand what is awaiting you.

216
00:09:55,500 --> 00:09:57,740
 And what he's going to describe to Timothy

217
00:09:57,740 --> 00:10:02,740
 are some dangers that Timothy wouldn't normally expect.

218
00:10:04,220 --> 00:10:07,340
 And as he does so, we're going to learn

219
00:10:07,340 --> 00:10:10,980
 of three specific dangers that we would not normally expect

220
00:10:10,980 --> 00:10:14,140
 within our own lives.

221
00:10:14,140 --> 00:10:15,300
 And so we're just going to dive into them.

222
00:10:15,300 --> 00:10:17,620
 I'm going to roll them out for you little by little.

223
00:10:17,620 --> 00:10:21,060
 So starting off chapter three, verse one, he says this,

224
00:10:21,060 --> 00:10:24,700
 but understand this Timothy, that in the last days,

225
00:10:24,700 --> 00:10:27,260
 there will come times of difficulty.

226
00:10:27,260 --> 00:10:29,020
 Now we'll stop because before we keep going,

227
00:10:29,020 --> 00:10:31,780
 we need to understand what he means by the last days,

228
00:10:31,780 --> 00:10:33,180
 because you might read that and think,

229
00:10:33,180 --> 00:10:35,620
 does that mean like the end of the world?

230
00:10:35,620 --> 00:10:37,260
 That's not what this means.

231
00:10:37,260 --> 00:10:39,700
 Just to give you the shortcut to it,

232
00:10:39,700 --> 00:10:43,260
 the last days is representative of the church age,

233
00:10:43,260 --> 00:10:45,800
 the age between when Jesus ascended into heaven,

234
00:10:45,800 --> 00:10:48,860
 he died, rose, and then he ascended back to the father.

235
00:10:48,860 --> 00:10:51,540
 And then it's the time between that book end

236
00:10:51,540 --> 00:10:54,300
 to when he returns at the end of time.

237
00:10:54,300 --> 00:10:55,940
 That's the last days.

238
00:10:55,940 --> 00:10:58,740
 What Paul just said is that it's in the last days

239
00:10:58,740 --> 00:11:00,620
 that difficulty will come,

240
00:11:00,620 --> 00:11:02,140
 which is important for us to understand

241
00:11:02,140 --> 00:11:03,620
 because if you consider the last days,

242
00:11:03,620 --> 00:11:05,100
 that's this moment right now,

243
00:11:05,100 --> 00:11:06,440
 that's the moment you live in.

244
00:11:06,440 --> 00:11:07,820
 We're a part of the church age.

245
00:11:07,820 --> 00:11:09,780
 Jesus ascended, we're waiting for him to come back.

246
00:11:09,780 --> 00:11:12,740
 And what Paul just said is there is difficulty

247
00:11:12,740 --> 00:11:15,740
 coming your way.

248
00:11:15,740 --> 00:11:17,720
 So what is the difficulty then?

249
00:11:17,720 --> 00:11:19,260
 Well, he tells us, keeps going.

250
00:11:19,260 --> 00:11:20,660
 He says in verse two,

251
00:11:20,660 --> 00:11:24,100
 "For people will be lovers of self,

252
00:11:24,100 --> 00:11:28,080
 "lovers of money, proud, arrogant, abusive,

253
00:11:28,080 --> 00:11:31,340
 "disobedient to their parents, ungrateful and unholy,

254
00:11:31,340 --> 00:11:33,820
 "heartless, unappeasable, slanderous,

255
00:11:33,820 --> 00:11:36,040
 "without self-control, brutal, not loving good,

256
00:11:36,040 --> 00:11:37,960
 "treacherous, reckless, swollen with conceit,

257
00:11:37,960 --> 00:11:41,540
 "lovers of pleasure rather than lovers of God."

258
00:11:41,540 --> 00:11:44,900
 Do you feel the list go on and on and on?

259
00:11:44,900 --> 00:11:47,300
 Paul is desperately trying to communicate

260
00:11:47,300 --> 00:11:49,900
 just how difficult the days ahead will be,

261
00:11:49,900 --> 00:11:54,140
 just how difficult the days at hand are.

262
00:11:54,140 --> 00:11:56,900
 That's fascinating.

263
00:11:58,180 --> 00:12:00,400
 When you read this,

264
00:12:00,400 --> 00:12:04,700
 you realize that the difficulty of our modern moment

265
00:12:04,700 --> 00:12:09,260
 is not the product of war or calamity or disease

266
00:12:09,260 --> 00:12:10,580
 or natural disaster.

267
00:12:10,580 --> 00:12:12,340
 It's not the product of any of those things.

268
00:12:12,340 --> 00:12:14,380
 What is it the product of?

269
00:12:14,380 --> 00:12:17,100
 The difficulty you're gonna face today

270
00:12:17,100 --> 00:12:19,700
 is the product of people.

271
00:12:19,700 --> 00:12:20,760
 We have a people problem.

272
00:12:20,760 --> 00:12:22,500
 That's what Paul's unpacking here.

273
00:12:22,500 --> 00:12:24,740
 He wants you to know, hey, the first danger

274
00:12:24,740 --> 00:12:26,500
 that you would least expect

275
00:12:26,500 --> 00:12:29,060
 is that people will exchange godly truth

276
00:12:29,060 --> 00:12:30,820
 for worldly wisdom.

277
00:12:30,820 --> 00:12:32,140
 That's your first point.

278
00:12:32,140 --> 00:12:35,580
 People will exchange godly truth for worldly wisdom

279
00:12:35,580 --> 00:12:37,140
 because as Paul is gonna tell us,

280
00:12:37,140 --> 00:12:38,700
 these aren't just any people.

281
00:12:38,700 --> 00:12:40,220
 He actually is going to tell us

282
00:12:40,220 --> 00:12:43,180
 these are people within the church.

283
00:12:43,180 --> 00:12:44,300
 He says so in verse five.

284
00:12:44,300 --> 00:12:46,340
 He says they have the appearance of godliness.

285
00:12:46,340 --> 00:12:48,420
 Anytime he uses that word godliness

286
00:12:48,420 --> 00:12:50,340
 over the course of the pastoral epistles

287
00:12:50,340 --> 00:12:52,220
 is representative of Christianity.

288
00:12:52,220 --> 00:12:53,820
 So they will be Christians.

289
00:12:53,820 --> 00:12:55,860
 They will appear as Christians,

290
00:12:55,860 --> 00:12:59,500
 have godliness, but they will deny its power.

291
00:12:59,500 --> 00:13:02,180
 You see, Paul is speaking about a people that,

292
00:13:02,180 --> 00:13:03,740
 man, they know God's truth,

293
00:13:03,740 --> 00:13:09,020
 but they exchanged it for the world's wisdom instead.

294
00:13:09,020 --> 00:13:09,860
 Why?

295
00:13:09,860 --> 00:13:10,680
 Why would they do that?

296
00:13:10,680 --> 00:13:13,460
 Well, why do you ever go get a second opinion?

297
00:13:13,460 --> 00:13:17,140
 Because you didn't like what you heard at first.

298
00:13:17,140 --> 00:13:19,040
 Like it didn't necessarily appeal

299
00:13:19,040 --> 00:13:20,980
 to whatever sort of outcome you were wanting.

300
00:13:20,980 --> 00:13:21,940
 And so you decided, you know what?

301
00:13:21,940 --> 00:13:23,980
 I'm gonna ask this person instead.

302
00:13:23,980 --> 00:13:24,820
 And maybe that one doesn't work.

303
00:13:24,820 --> 00:13:26,420
 And so you get a third opinion.

304
00:13:26,420 --> 00:13:27,860
 That's what's happening right here.

305
00:13:27,860 --> 00:13:29,540
 These people in Timothy's day,

306
00:13:29,540 --> 00:13:32,340
 as well as people within our present day,

307
00:13:32,340 --> 00:13:33,700
 they know what God says,

308
00:13:33,700 --> 00:13:35,260
 but they don't necessarily like it.

309
00:13:35,260 --> 00:13:37,500
 And so what they do is they punt on that

310
00:13:37,500 --> 00:13:38,780
 and they choose for themselves

311
00:13:38,780 --> 00:13:40,980
 instead what the world wants to recommend.

312
00:13:40,980 --> 00:13:43,500
 They'll look for teachings and advice and recommendations

313
00:13:43,500 --> 00:13:45,940
 that ultimately promote their self-interest.

314
00:13:45,940 --> 00:13:49,820
 Paul says it like this in the exact same letter.

315
00:13:49,820 --> 00:13:52,100
 He says in chapter four,

316
00:13:52,100 --> 00:13:53,540
 "For the time is coming when people

317
00:13:53,540 --> 00:13:56,060
 "will not endure sound teaching,

318
00:13:56,060 --> 00:13:57,380
 "but having itching ears,

319
00:13:57,380 --> 00:13:59,320
 "they will accumulate for themselves teachers

320
00:13:59,320 --> 00:14:00,900
 "that suit their own passions."

321
00:14:00,900 --> 00:14:01,920
 Do you hear it?

322
00:14:01,920 --> 00:14:05,940
 They're gonna exchange God's truth for worldly wisdom,

323
00:14:05,940 --> 00:14:08,580
 which fits their own desire.

324
00:14:08,580 --> 00:14:10,220
 And they're gonna turn away from listening to the truth

325
00:14:10,220 --> 00:14:13,300
 and they're gonna wander off into myths.

326
00:14:13,300 --> 00:14:15,460
 They're gonna have itching ears.

327
00:14:15,460 --> 00:14:17,820
 They're gonna be like my dog when I was a boy.

328
00:14:17,820 --> 00:14:19,640
 I had a golden retriever.

329
00:14:19,640 --> 00:14:21,020
 And man, the minute I would come outside,

330
00:14:21,020 --> 00:14:22,880
 he would get as close to me as he could.

331
00:14:22,880 --> 00:14:25,460
 And if I didn't pet him, he would get even closer to me

332
00:14:25,460 --> 00:14:28,500
 until the point at which big dog is now sitting in my lap.

333
00:14:28,500 --> 00:14:29,980
 He's desperate for me to what?

334
00:14:29,980 --> 00:14:32,820
 To itch his ears, to pet him behind the ear.

335
00:14:32,820 --> 00:14:34,860
 And so if I'm not doing that, what's he gonna do?

336
00:14:34,860 --> 00:14:36,460
 He's going to get up from my lap

337
00:14:36,460 --> 00:14:39,060
 and he's going to find the next suitable person

338
00:14:39,060 --> 00:14:40,500
 who will give him what he wants.

339
00:14:40,500 --> 00:14:41,780
 That's what Paul's describing.

340
00:14:41,780 --> 00:14:44,700
 He's like, hey, there are believers,

341
00:14:44,700 --> 00:14:46,780
 people that have the appearance of godliness

342
00:14:46,780 --> 00:14:48,660
 that are ultimately going to behave like that.

343
00:14:48,660 --> 00:14:50,300
 They are going to run wherever it is

344
00:14:50,300 --> 00:14:52,020
 they can get the kind of attention

345
00:14:52,020 --> 00:14:53,940
 that they're wanting.

346
00:14:53,940 --> 00:14:56,920
 Now, here's the thing you have to know.

347
00:14:56,920 --> 00:14:59,960
 Even though we live in a day where

348
00:14:59,960 --> 00:15:02,140
 if people don't like what the word has to say,

349
00:15:02,140 --> 00:15:03,760
 they'll just go to the world instead.

350
00:15:03,760 --> 00:15:05,540
 The teachings that we face now,

351
00:15:05,540 --> 00:15:07,920
 the false prophecies that are prevalent

352
00:15:07,920 --> 00:15:10,280
 in our current culture,

353
00:15:10,280 --> 00:15:13,120
 they are admittedly somewhat different

354
00:15:13,120 --> 00:15:15,320
 than what Timothy was facing in his time.

355
00:15:15,320 --> 00:15:17,680
 There are certainly ones that are similar,

356
00:15:17,680 --> 00:15:19,760
 but there are certainly ones that are different.

357
00:15:19,760 --> 00:15:21,340
 And yet here's what you need to know.

358
00:15:21,340 --> 00:15:22,560
 Though the false teachings of today

359
00:15:22,560 --> 00:15:26,420
 don't necessarily match the false teachings back then,

360
00:15:26,420 --> 00:15:29,920
 the results are nonetheless the same.

361
00:15:29,920 --> 00:15:34,020
 People, they stop walking in godliness

362
00:15:34,020 --> 00:15:37,600
 and they start walking in godlessness.

363
00:15:37,600 --> 00:15:38,920
 That's what happens.

364
00:15:38,920 --> 00:15:42,220
 To the point that Paul gives you this

365
00:15:42,220 --> 00:15:45,520
 laundry list of descriptors,

366
00:15:45,520 --> 00:15:49,820
 these false virtues that accord with these false teachings.

367
00:15:49,820 --> 00:15:52,540
 Now, I was really torn about how to teach

368
00:15:52,540 --> 00:15:55,760
 this specific section because it's 18 different words.

369
00:15:55,760 --> 00:15:57,140
 And we don't necessarily have the time

370
00:15:57,140 --> 00:16:00,620
 to unpack the Greek behind every single one of those words.

371
00:16:00,620 --> 00:16:01,580
 If you want to learn that,

372
00:16:01,580 --> 00:16:05,140
 you should go pull up an interlinear commentary

373
00:16:05,140 --> 00:16:07,460
 and understand what do these words specifically mean.

374
00:16:07,460 --> 00:16:08,940
 But what I thought would be most helpful to you

375
00:16:08,940 --> 00:16:11,900
 is to take some of these descriptors

376
00:16:11,900 --> 00:16:16,040
 and help you identify the actual false teaching

377
00:16:16,040 --> 00:16:19,860
 that leads to their development.

378
00:16:19,860 --> 00:16:21,100
 I'm not going to give you all of them,

379
00:16:21,100 --> 00:16:22,260
 but I do want to give you some

380
00:16:22,260 --> 00:16:24,540
 because I think it's important that we realize, man,

381
00:16:24,540 --> 00:16:29,240
 there are false truths being propagated in our culture

382
00:16:29,240 --> 00:16:30,620
 that so many of us are subject to

383
00:16:30,620 --> 00:16:32,540
 and we don't even know it.

384
00:16:32,540 --> 00:16:34,180
 So let's just take a couple of them, yeah?

385
00:16:34,180 --> 00:16:35,200
 Does that sound good to you?

386
00:16:35,200 --> 00:16:36,140
 Y'all tracking with me?

387
00:16:36,140 --> 00:16:36,980
 Are you out there?

388
00:16:36,980 --> 00:16:38,120
 Shake your heads if you're there.

389
00:16:38,120 --> 00:16:39,580
 Gotcha, I see you.

390
00:16:39,580 --> 00:16:40,760
 Thank you.

391
00:16:40,760 --> 00:16:44,620
 The first one is what makes someone a lover of self?

392
00:16:44,620 --> 00:16:46,280
 It would be a false teaching like,

393
00:16:46,280 --> 00:16:48,340
 "If it doesn't serve you, then let it go."

394
00:16:48,340 --> 00:16:53,120
 This is classic self-help gospel.

395
00:16:53,120 --> 00:16:55,520
 This idea that you matter most.

396
00:16:55,520 --> 00:16:57,040
 Like, so if your commitments

397
00:16:57,040 --> 00:16:58,680
 or if they're really wearing you out,

398
00:16:58,680 --> 00:16:59,800
 then man, just drop those things.

399
00:16:59,800 --> 00:17:00,700
 You don't have to do that.

400
00:17:00,700 --> 00:17:03,540
 Or if your job is not fulfilling the way that you expected,

401
00:17:03,540 --> 00:17:04,380
 then you can just quit.

402
00:17:04,380 --> 00:17:05,200
 You can move on.

403
00:17:05,200 --> 00:17:06,040
 You can do something different.

404
00:17:06,040 --> 00:17:07,420
 Or hey, if you don't want to go to that thing

405
00:17:07,420 --> 00:17:08,540
 because you thought those people were going,

406
00:17:08,540 --> 00:17:09,700
 but they're not going any longer, you know what?

407
00:17:09,700 --> 00:17:12,000
 Then just make up a little lie and a dip.

408
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:13,120
 That way you don't have to go

409
00:17:13,120 --> 00:17:14,840
 and do something that you don't want to do.

410
00:17:14,840 --> 00:17:16,740
 This is classic self-help gospel.

411
00:17:16,740 --> 00:17:17,580
 You matter most.

412
00:17:17,580 --> 00:17:18,600
 And so if it's not serving you,

413
00:17:18,600 --> 00:17:20,400
 then don't worry about doing it.

414
00:17:20,400 --> 00:17:21,920
 And yet here's the thing.

415
00:17:21,920 --> 00:17:24,040
 That's so un-gospel.

416
00:17:24,040 --> 00:17:28,340
 Because we don't serve ourselves.

417
00:17:28,340 --> 00:17:31,500
 We deny ourselves.

418
00:17:31,500 --> 00:17:35,520
 We're not a people that seek to serve ourselves.

419
00:17:35,520 --> 00:17:37,880
 We are people that seek to serve others,

420
00:17:37,880 --> 00:17:40,220
 even at great cost to ourself.

421
00:17:40,220 --> 00:17:41,580
 This is a false teaching.

422
00:17:41,580 --> 00:17:44,160
 And it's one that some of you are believing.

423
00:17:44,160 --> 00:17:46,080
 How do you become proud?

424
00:17:46,080 --> 00:17:47,880
 Well, it might be by way of a false teaching,

425
00:17:47,880 --> 00:17:50,320
 like God won't give you more than you can handle.

426
00:17:50,320 --> 00:17:54,480
 No, God actually will give you more than you can handle.

427
00:17:54,480 --> 00:17:55,640
 You know why?

428
00:17:55,640 --> 00:17:58,760
 Because he doesn't want you relying on your own strength.

429
00:17:58,760 --> 00:18:00,960
 He doesn't want you rolling out of bed every morning

430
00:18:00,960 --> 00:18:02,040
 and being like, you know what?

431
00:18:02,040 --> 00:18:02,880
 I've got this thing.

432
00:18:02,880 --> 00:18:04,400
 Everybody, don't worry.

433
00:18:04,400 --> 00:18:07,080
 Life's hard, but I'm tougher.

434
00:18:07,080 --> 00:18:08,560
 You know, like that's not the perspective

435
00:18:08,560 --> 00:18:09,400
 that he wants you to have.

436
00:18:09,400 --> 00:18:10,480
 He wants you to know, hey, no,

437
00:18:10,480 --> 00:18:12,600
 this world is going to be a lot to handle,

438
00:18:12,600 --> 00:18:15,720
 so much in fact that you can't handle it by yourself,

439
00:18:15,720 --> 00:18:18,560
 but I can handle it for you.

440
00:18:18,560 --> 00:18:19,960
 You don't have the strength it takes,

441
00:18:19,960 --> 00:18:22,460
 but I have the strength it takes instead.

442
00:18:22,460 --> 00:18:24,180
 How do you become arrogant?

443
00:18:24,180 --> 00:18:25,120
 You believe something like,

444
00:18:25,120 --> 00:18:27,480
 well, God helps those who help themselves.

445
00:18:27,480 --> 00:18:30,320
 I remember I had a roommate who had that phrase,

446
00:18:30,320 --> 00:18:32,280
 God helps those who help themselves

447
00:18:32,280 --> 00:18:36,200
 on a poster hung in his college bedroom.

448
00:18:36,200 --> 00:18:37,300
 And I remember looking at it and thinking,

449
00:18:37,300 --> 00:18:39,360
 man, that is extremely motivating.

450
00:18:39,360 --> 00:18:41,160
 God helps those who help themselves.

451
00:18:41,160 --> 00:18:45,360
 And then I realized it's extremely wrong

452
00:18:45,360 --> 00:18:47,400
 because God doesn't help those who help themselves.

453
00:18:47,400 --> 00:18:50,820
 He helps those who cannot help themselves.

454
00:18:50,820 --> 00:18:53,160
 Like when we were dead in our trespasses and sins,

455
00:18:53,160 --> 00:18:55,000
 then he made us alive together with Christ.

456
00:18:55,000 --> 00:18:55,920
 You see how that works?

457
00:18:55,920 --> 00:18:59,040
 You don't do anything to contribute

458
00:18:59,040 --> 00:19:02,000
 to the ultimate salvation you receive from Christ.

459
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:04,020
 You trust in him wholeheartedly.

460
00:19:04,020 --> 00:19:05,280
 You can't help yourself.

461
00:19:05,280 --> 00:19:06,760
 You are in fact helpless,

462
00:19:06,760 --> 00:19:08,760
 but we know where our help comes from.

463
00:19:09,760 --> 00:19:12,960
 How do you become disobedient to your parents?

464
00:19:12,960 --> 00:19:14,280
 Some of you are like, don't worry, man.

465
00:19:14,280 --> 00:19:15,460
 I've already got that one.

466
00:19:15,460 --> 00:19:17,880
 This is not talking about parents in specific.

467
00:19:17,880 --> 00:19:19,080
 Really what this is talking about is

468
00:19:19,080 --> 00:19:22,440
 how do we become disobedient to authority in our life?

469
00:19:22,440 --> 00:19:24,800
 And the way that it happens is we subject ourselves

470
00:19:24,800 --> 00:19:27,760
 to the false teaching of your way is the right way.

471
00:19:27,760 --> 00:19:29,760
 Like, hey man, you do you, bro.

472
00:19:29,760 --> 00:19:33,440
 Like, if you want to be furry, go for it.

473
00:19:33,440 --> 00:19:36,080
 You want to trust in horoscopes to predict your future?

474
00:19:36,080 --> 00:19:37,760
 Right on, man, whatever you want.

475
00:19:37,760 --> 00:19:38,840
 You think the world is flat?

476
00:19:38,840 --> 00:19:39,680
 Don't fall off.

477
00:19:39,680 --> 00:19:41,000
 You know, like this is the way

478
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:42,840
 that we think about our culture.

479
00:19:42,840 --> 00:19:46,080
 Like we let people follow their own way,

480
00:19:46,080 --> 00:19:49,640
 but the reality is we know there is only one way,

481
00:19:49,640 --> 00:19:52,920
 one truth, and one life, and it is Jesus.

482
00:19:52,920 --> 00:19:55,040
 And so you don't get to follow

483
00:19:55,040 --> 00:19:57,040
 whatever course you set for yourself

484
00:19:57,040 --> 00:19:59,640
 and thus become disobedient to authority.

485
00:19:59,640 --> 00:20:03,380
 You ultimately need to choose to follow the right way,

486
00:20:03,380 --> 00:20:04,920
 which is God's way.

487
00:20:04,920 --> 00:20:06,840
 And this is a total aside.

488
00:20:06,840 --> 00:20:10,360
 I just think this is crazily the original sin.

489
00:20:10,360 --> 00:20:13,000
 Like, have you thought about that?

490
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:14,480
 Like, hey, you know what?

491
00:20:14,480 --> 00:20:18,080
 Did God really say, no, you can go your own way.

492
00:20:18,080 --> 00:20:20,360
 You can do your own thing.

493
00:20:20,360 --> 00:20:25,360
 And yet the truth is when we could not work our way back,

494
00:20:25,360 --> 00:20:28,540
 Christ came and made a way instead.

495
00:20:28,540 --> 00:20:32,080
 How do you become heartless?

496
00:20:32,080 --> 00:20:34,840
 You buy into the lie that,

497
00:20:34,840 --> 00:20:36,940
 man, nobody's perfect and neither are you.

498
00:20:36,940 --> 00:20:43,360
 That's true, but we don't say it in a way

499
00:20:43,360 --> 00:20:44,840
 where we're agreeing with God.

500
00:20:44,840 --> 00:20:48,460
 We say it in a way where we present an excuse for our sin.

501
00:20:48,460 --> 00:20:51,820
 How about slanderous?

502
00:20:51,820 --> 00:20:56,460
 Something like, hey, it's healthy to process out loud,

503
00:20:56,460 --> 00:20:58,080
 but it's not healthy when you're processing

504
00:20:58,080 --> 00:20:59,840
 because it's gossiping.

505
00:20:59,840 --> 00:21:02,160
 Because gossiping isn't healthy, it's actually hurtful.

506
00:21:02,160 --> 00:21:03,000
 It tears people down.

507
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:04,160
 It doesn't build them up.

508
00:21:04,880 --> 00:21:07,620
 How about without self-control?

509
00:21:07,620 --> 00:21:09,760
 Just listen to your heart.

510
00:21:09,760 --> 00:21:11,200
 That's a horrible piece of advice

511
00:21:11,200 --> 00:21:12,200
 that the world is propagating

512
00:21:12,200 --> 00:21:15,000
 and we have accepted within our church.

513
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:17,000
 And yet the truth of the matter is so many people,

514
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:19,160
 they are following their feelings

515
00:21:19,160 --> 00:21:21,400
 as opposed to taking captive their thoughts,

516
00:21:21,400 --> 00:21:25,240
 mastering their flesh and disciplining their bodies.

517
00:21:25,240 --> 00:21:29,040
 How do you become someone who doesn't love good?

518
00:21:29,040 --> 00:21:32,640
 You buy into the lie that you gotta be a little bad

519
00:21:32,640 --> 00:21:33,800
 to have a little fun.

520
00:21:33,800 --> 00:21:36,960
 We do this.

521
00:21:36,960 --> 00:21:40,020
 Our generation is notorious for this one.

522
00:21:40,020 --> 00:21:45,000
 We feel like we can't go out on the weekends

523
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:47,140
 unless we're gonna bend some rules.

524
00:21:47,140 --> 00:21:50,240
 We lament going to weddings if there is no alcohol.

525
00:21:50,240 --> 00:21:53,480
 We listen to music that dehumanizes women.

526
00:21:53,480 --> 00:21:56,760
 We're willing to watch TV shows that absolutely have nudity,

527
00:21:56,760 --> 00:21:57,600
 but you know what?

528
00:21:57,600 --> 00:21:59,260
 What good TV show doesn't have that nowadays?

529
00:21:59,260 --> 00:22:02,000
 We're willing to be a little bad to have a little fun.

530
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:04,840
 And in the process, what we do is we entertain the very sin

531
00:22:04,840 --> 00:22:06,880
 that Christ went to the cross to die for.

532
00:22:06,880 --> 00:22:10,000
 I'll give you a couple more.

533
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:13,200
 How do you become, I'll give you one more.

534
00:22:13,200 --> 00:22:15,880
 How do you become a lover of pleasure?

535
00:22:15,880 --> 00:22:18,520
 You buy into the idea that God wants you to be happy.

536
00:22:18,520 --> 00:22:20,800
 And I actually don't disagree with this.

537
00:22:20,800 --> 00:22:24,080
 I genuinely believe that God does want you to have life

538
00:22:24,080 --> 00:22:25,760
 and have life abundantly,

539
00:22:25,760 --> 00:22:28,520
 but he cares deeply about where you're finding

540
00:22:28,520 --> 00:22:29,880
 your source of satisfaction,

541
00:22:29,880 --> 00:22:31,880
 where it is you're finding your happiness.

542
00:22:31,880 --> 00:22:33,680
 He's not wanting you to find it

543
00:22:33,680 --> 00:22:35,200
 by way of the American dream.

544
00:22:35,200 --> 00:22:38,320
 It's not gonna be found in owning a big house

545
00:22:38,320 --> 00:22:40,680
 and wearing fancy clothes and having a great job

546
00:22:40,680 --> 00:22:42,560
 and hooking up with an amazing wife or husband.

547
00:22:42,560 --> 00:22:44,000
 Like that's not the way this is gonna work.

548
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:45,640
 You're not gonna find happiness in those things.

549
00:22:45,640 --> 00:22:48,080
 Can those things contribute to your satisfaction?

550
00:22:48,080 --> 00:22:51,380
 Certainly, but only so far as they lead you to delight

551
00:22:51,380 --> 00:22:54,120
 in the God that gave them to you.

552
00:22:54,120 --> 00:22:57,440
 That's the only way then God can make you happy.

553
00:22:57,440 --> 00:23:01,560
 Again, these are just some examples given from Paul's list.

554
00:23:01,560 --> 00:23:03,160
 We could go through all of them again.

555
00:23:03,160 --> 00:23:05,320
 And if you want to understand what the false teachings

556
00:23:05,320 --> 00:23:06,520
 might be behind some of these others,

557
00:23:06,520 --> 00:23:09,000
 you can come find me after service or drop me an email,

558
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:10,600
 but I just wanna put them in front of you

559
00:23:10,600 --> 00:23:12,560
 because sometimes we read about false teaching

560
00:23:12,560 --> 00:23:14,320
 and we think, man, that's a thing of the past.

561
00:23:14,320 --> 00:23:15,880
 That's something that happened in the scripture.

562
00:23:15,880 --> 00:23:19,360
 Jesus and Paul and Peter, they were big on false prophecy,

563
00:23:19,360 --> 00:23:21,320
 but that's not really something that we deal with right now.

564
00:23:21,320 --> 00:23:24,000
 No, we certainly deal with it right now.

565
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:25,360
 And if you haven't included already,

566
00:23:25,360 --> 00:23:27,600
 that's what this entire talk is gonna be about.

567
00:23:27,600 --> 00:23:28,480
 So let's just keep going

568
00:23:28,480 --> 00:23:31,600
 because second point continues in verse five.

569
00:23:31,600 --> 00:23:35,040
 He says, "Wicked men or wicked women

570
00:23:35,040 --> 00:23:36,480
 "will have the appearance of godliness,

571
00:23:36,480 --> 00:23:37,680
 "but they'll deny its power.

572
00:23:37,680 --> 00:23:40,080
 "Avoid these people."

573
00:23:40,080 --> 00:23:43,760
 Paul's saying the second danger that we need to know,

574
00:23:43,760 --> 00:23:44,840
 but we may not expect,

575
00:23:44,840 --> 00:23:47,780
 is that Christians can look the part, but lack the heart.

576
00:23:47,780 --> 00:23:51,960
 And keyword there is Christians.

577
00:23:51,960 --> 00:23:56,040
 Christians can look the part, but lack the heart.

578
00:23:56,040 --> 00:23:57,240
 It's interesting.

579
00:23:57,240 --> 00:24:02,160
 When Paul's writing to Timothy in this moment,

580
00:24:02,160 --> 00:24:05,360
 he's actually writing a piece of prophetic literature

581
00:24:05,360 --> 00:24:07,280
 because he's not speaking about the problems

582
00:24:07,280 --> 00:24:09,560
 Timothy is facing in his current day,

583
00:24:09,560 --> 00:24:12,600
 but the problems that we will face in our current day.

584
00:24:12,600 --> 00:24:15,560
 When he talks about the last days,

585
00:24:15,560 --> 00:24:18,520
 he's talking about our days.

586
00:24:18,520 --> 00:24:20,200
 And you know what the problem is?

587
00:24:20,200 --> 00:24:24,580
 There will be wicked men, there will be wicked women

588
00:24:24,580 --> 00:24:29,520
 who have all the markings of a Christian,

589
00:24:29,520 --> 00:24:32,000
 but they will have none of the makings of Christ.

590
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:37,060
 They will look exteriorly like him,

591
00:24:37,060 --> 00:24:40,580
 but they will not look interiorly like him.

592
00:24:40,580 --> 00:24:42,280
 That's what Paul means

593
00:24:42,280 --> 00:24:45,200
 when he uses the word appearance right here.

594
00:24:45,200 --> 00:24:48,480
 That word appearance is the Greek word morphe.

595
00:24:48,480 --> 00:24:51,960
 It's where you get words like morphology,

596
00:24:51,960 --> 00:24:53,600
 the study of shape and structure,

597
00:24:53,600 --> 00:24:55,200
 which is actually what morphe represents,

598
00:24:55,200 --> 00:24:58,600
 or ectomorphic, endomorphic, mesomorphic,

599
00:24:58,600 --> 00:25:01,320
 the idea of different structural body types,

600
00:25:01,320 --> 00:25:02,560
 or metamorphosis,

601
00:25:02,560 --> 00:25:05,020
 which is probably the most accessible word in this room,

602
00:25:05,020 --> 00:25:07,080
 the idea that a tadpole becomes a frog.

603
00:25:07,080 --> 00:25:08,040
 What happens?

604
00:25:08,040 --> 00:25:10,480
 That creature changes its structure.

605
00:25:10,480 --> 00:25:12,800
 It adopts a new shape.

606
00:25:12,800 --> 00:25:15,920
 What he's really trying to get you to understand

607
00:25:15,920 --> 00:25:19,200
 is that there will be people in this life

608
00:25:19,200 --> 00:25:21,280
 who have the shape of a Christian,

609
00:25:21,280 --> 00:25:24,020
 but they lack the substance of a Christian.

610
00:25:24,020 --> 00:25:29,540
 They will be like a perfume bottle filled with water.

611
00:25:29,540 --> 00:25:34,160
 They will look beautiful on the outside,

612
00:25:34,160 --> 00:25:37,060
 but there will be no beauty on the inside.

613
00:25:37,060 --> 00:25:39,440
 They will appear believable,

614
00:25:39,440 --> 00:25:44,000
 but they don't actually believe.

615
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:46,080
 And according to Paul,

616
00:25:46,080 --> 00:25:50,280
 this is the greatest threat facing modern Christianity.

617
00:25:50,280 --> 00:25:52,120
 The greatest threat there is.

618
00:25:52,120 --> 00:25:54,960
 The greatest threat is not religious persecution,

619
00:25:54,960 --> 00:25:57,280
 though that certainly happens in our world.

620
00:25:57,280 --> 00:25:59,320
 It's not social exclusion,

621
00:25:59,320 --> 00:26:01,040
 though you will face some of that

622
00:26:01,040 --> 00:26:03,200
 as people push you to the wayside because of your belief.

623
00:26:03,200 --> 00:26:04,680
 And it's not personal deconstruction,

624
00:26:04,680 --> 00:26:06,660
 though some of you are in the midst of that right now.

625
00:26:06,660 --> 00:26:08,060
 It's none of those things.

626
00:26:08,060 --> 00:26:12,360
 The greatest threat facing modern Christianity is hypocrisy.

627
00:26:12,360 --> 00:26:14,960
 That's it.

628
00:26:14,960 --> 00:26:19,840
 It's those that appear one way, but they act another way.

629
00:26:19,840 --> 00:26:22,800
 And it's as much a danger in this room as it is in any.

630
00:26:22,800 --> 00:26:24,100
 I'll just level with you.

631
00:26:24,100 --> 00:26:27,760
 There is something within people,

632
00:26:27,760 --> 00:26:29,440
 particularly young adults,

633
00:26:29,440 --> 00:26:32,520
 that cares more what the world sees of them on the outside

634
00:26:32,520 --> 00:26:35,360
 than what the world sees of them on the inside.

635
00:26:35,360 --> 00:26:36,200
 If you don't believe me,

636
00:26:36,200 --> 00:26:39,160
 like this is why we embellish stories.

637
00:26:39,160 --> 00:26:41,160
 Like we find ourselves in moments

638
00:26:41,160 --> 00:26:42,480
 where we're telling a story,

639
00:26:42,480 --> 00:26:44,960
 but it doesn't feel like the truth is actually sufficient.

640
00:26:44,960 --> 00:26:47,600
 So we stretch the truth and we make a fishtail out of it

641
00:26:47,600 --> 00:26:49,960
 because we really want to impress the people around us.

642
00:26:49,960 --> 00:26:51,680
 You do this, I do this.

643
00:26:51,680 --> 00:26:52,840
 Like this is something we do.

644
00:26:52,840 --> 00:26:55,120
 Why? Because we want people to like us.

645
00:26:55,120 --> 00:26:57,760
 Or maybe it's not that, maybe it's why we pad our resumes.

646
00:26:57,760 --> 00:26:59,540
 Anybody applying for a job?

647
00:26:59,540 --> 00:27:01,480
 You've probably padded your resume some

648
00:27:01,480 --> 00:27:03,920
 because you want it to come across someone's desk and what?

649
00:27:03,920 --> 00:27:04,760
 Impress them.

650
00:27:04,760 --> 00:27:06,680
 Like that makes complete and total sense

651
00:27:06,680 --> 00:27:08,680
 in the eyes of our world.

652
00:27:08,680 --> 00:27:11,600
 Or maybe it's why you slip casually

653
00:27:11,600 --> 00:27:13,100
 that really good thing you did,

654
00:27:13,100 --> 00:27:16,240
 that super Christian thing you did into conversations,

655
00:27:16,240 --> 00:27:18,160
 even though we weren't really talking about that.

656
00:27:18,160 --> 00:27:19,720
 But I guess now we're talking about that

657
00:27:19,720 --> 00:27:21,280
 because you want us to talk about you.

658
00:27:21,280 --> 00:27:25,080
 Maybe it's not that, maybe it's why you tell half truths.

659
00:27:25,080 --> 00:27:28,040
 Like you just, you don't want to lie,

660
00:27:28,040 --> 00:27:30,860
 but you also don't necessarily want to be perceived as bad.

661
00:27:30,860 --> 00:27:33,520
 And so you just offer some of the truth,

662
00:27:33,520 --> 00:27:36,060
 but you seem to withhold what isn't true

663
00:27:36,060 --> 00:27:39,600
 in the hopes that it preserves your reputation.

664
00:27:39,600 --> 00:27:41,360
 For some of us, I think this is hilarious.

665
00:27:41,360 --> 00:27:43,040
 We change the way we talk

666
00:27:43,040 --> 00:27:45,880
 depending upon the group of people we're with.

667
00:27:45,880 --> 00:27:49,480
 We adopt a different accent or a tone of voice

668
00:27:49,480 --> 00:27:52,200
 depending upon which crew we find ourselves within.

669
00:27:52,200 --> 00:27:53,960
 And the reason why is we just want to look cool.

670
00:27:53,960 --> 00:27:55,920
 Like we just want to be adopted by them.

671
00:27:55,920 --> 00:27:58,000
 There are endless examples I could go through,

672
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:00,200
 but here's the thing, and I want you to catch this point.

673
00:28:00,200 --> 00:28:02,780
 We care a lot about what people think of us externally,

674
00:28:02,780 --> 00:28:04,640
 but do you know what God cares about?

675
00:28:04,640 --> 00:28:07,440
 He tells us.

676
00:28:07,440 --> 00:28:08,920
 First Samuel 16, he says,

677
00:28:08,920 --> 00:28:11,040
 "But the Lord said to Samuel," talking about Saul,

678
00:28:11,040 --> 00:28:13,380
 "Do not look on his appearance

679
00:28:13,380 --> 00:28:16,680
 "or on the height of his stature, because I've rejected him.

680
00:28:16,680 --> 00:28:18,700
 "For the Lord sees not as man sees.

681
00:28:18,700 --> 00:28:20,080
 "Man looks on the outward appearance,

682
00:28:20,080 --> 00:28:24,680
 "but the Lord looks on the heart."

683
00:28:24,680 --> 00:28:28,040
 He looks on the heart.

684
00:28:28,040 --> 00:28:32,620
 It doesn't say he might look on the heart.

685
00:28:32,620 --> 00:28:33,840
 So maybe you could be in the clear.

686
00:28:33,840 --> 00:28:34,920
 Maybe he won't check you out.

687
00:28:34,920 --> 00:28:38,260
 It doesn't say he will look on the heart.

688
00:28:38,260 --> 00:28:39,800
 So you've got some time to clean yourself up

689
00:28:39,800 --> 00:28:40,740
 and get yourself ready.

690
00:28:40,740 --> 00:28:44,400
 It says he does look on the heart.

691
00:28:44,400 --> 00:28:46,440
 So let me ask you, Porch,

692
00:28:46,440 --> 00:28:48,520
 what does he see when he looks on yours?

693
00:28:48,520 --> 00:28:54,420
 When he looks on your heart, what is it that God sees?

694
00:28:54,420 --> 00:28:59,420
 Does he see someone that is passionately engaging

695
00:28:59,420 --> 00:29:01,280
 in worship, or does he see someone

696
00:29:01,280 --> 00:29:04,100
 that is passively singing along?

697
00:29:04,100 --> 00:29:07,940
 Does he see someone that's praying in secret,

698
00:29:07,940 --> 00:29:10,540
 or does he see someone that only prays in public?

699
00:29:10,540 --> 00:29:13,280
 Does he see someone who is serving the church,

700
00:29:13,280 --> 00:29:15,720
 or actually only someone that is hoping

701
00:29:15,720 --> 00:29:17,540
 the church will serve them?

702
00:29:17,540 --> 00:29:20,420
 Does he see someone that is recognizing opportunity

703
00:29:20,420 --> 00:29:22,620
 to do good, or does he see someone

704
00:29:22,620 --> 00:29:26,780
 that only recognizes opportunity to be seen?

705
00:29:26,780 --> 00:29:30,560
 Does he see someone who's reading the word by themself

706
00:29:30,560 --> 00:29:32,280
 on Wednesday morning, or just someone

707
00:29:32,280 --> 00:29:34,340
 that's reading the word when we're all reading the word

708
00:29:34,340 --> 00:29:36,400
 here on Tuesday night?

709
00:29:36,400 --> 00:29:39,760
 Does he see someone that desires more of him

710
00:29:39,760 --> 00:29:42,440
 rather than someone that just desires more from him?

711
00:29:42,440 --> 00:29:45,820
 And here's the thing.

712
00:29:45,820 --> 00:29:49,800
 I know as I ask questions like this,

713
00:29:49,800 --> 00:29:54,080
 it can feel pretty offensive.

714
00:29:54,080 --> 00:29:56,720
 It can feel like I'm trying to target you,

715
00:29:56,720 --> 00:29:58,400
 and that's not what I'm doing.

716
00:29:58,400 --> 00:30:00,720
 I'm not trying to be offensive to you.

717
00:30:00,720 --> 00:30:03,940
 I'm not trying to put you on the defense in any kind of way.

718
00:30:03,940 --> 00:30:06,140
 I'm trying to be honest with you.

719
00:30:07,040 --> 00:30:09,560
 When Jesus, excuse me, when the scriptures

720
00:30:09,560 --> 00:30:10,840
 talk about false teachers,

721
00:30:10,840 --> 00:30:14,040
 it is elevated to a place of priority.

722
00:30:14,040 --> 00:30:16,960
 So much so that Jesus' last public sermon

723
00:30:16,960 --> 00:30:18,960
 was about this specific topic.

724
00:30:18,960 --> 00:30:21,920
 He cared that much when speaking to the masses

725
00:30:21,920 --> 00:30:23,540
 that we would get this.

726
00:30:23,540 --> 00:30:27,160
 It's here in Paul's final letter that he's addressing it

727
00:30:27,160 --> 00:30:29,600
 in what is one of the concluding sections.

728
00:30:29,600 --> 00:30:30,720
 This stuff matters.

729
00:30:30,720 --> 00:30:32,600
 I'm not trying to put you on the defense.

730
00:30:32,600 --> 00:30:36,280
 I am trying to be honest with you.

731
00:30:36,280 --> 00:30:38,880
 Because when Paul says something as serious as,

732
00:30:38,880 --> 00:30:40,820
 they have the appearance of godliness,

733
00:30:40,820 --> 00:30:42,500
 but they deny its power,

734
00:30:42,500 --> 00:30:47,020
 that should cause us to do some internal investigation.

735
00:30:47,020 --> 00:30:52,320
 So listen to me, I love you enough to say this,

736
00:30:52,320 --> 00:30:55,340
 because I think Paul is saying the same.

737
00:30:55,340 --> 00:31:01,220
 Some of you think you're Christians in here, and you're not.

738
00:31:04,560 --> 00:31:07,640
 And I know the minute I say that in a room like this,

739
00:31:07,640 --> 00:31:09,800
 like defenses go up.

740
00:31:09,800 --> 00:31:13,120
 And some of you are deeply concerned about what I just said.

741
00:31:13,120 --> 00:31:15,840
 And the reality is for those that feel offended,

742
00:31:15,840 --> 00:31:19,140
 it's often those that need to do

743
00:31:19,140 --> 00:31:21,680
 some of the deep inner searching.

744
00:31:21,680 --> 00:31:23,200
 Because I've never met a believer

745
00:31:23,200 --> 00:31:24,880
 where this question's been raised,

746
00:31:24,880 --> 00:31:28,520
 where they've been confused or concerned

747
00:31:28,520 --> 00:31:31,840
 about reconfirming their confidence in Christ.

748
00:31:31,840 --> 00:31:33,920
 Every believer that is asked,

749
00:31:33,920 --> 00:31:36,520
 "Hey, do you actually think you're saved?"

750
00:31:36,520 --> 00:31:38,320
 They're all like, "Yeah, man, let me reevaluate."

751
00:31:38,320 --> 00:31:40,200
 Absolutely, I am.

752
00:31:40,200 --> 00:31:41,360
 I know where my hope comes from.

753
00:31:41,360 --> 00:31:43,680
 It doesn't come from me, it comes from him.

754
00:31:43,680 --> 00:31:45,920
 And so let me be abundantly clear.

755
00:31:45,920 --> 00:31:49,360
 Like, you're not a Christian because you have morals.

756
00:31:49,360 --> 00:31:51,100
 You're not a Christian because you grew up

757
00:31:51,100 --> 00:31:52,200
 in a family of faith.

758
00:31:52,200 --> 00:31:54,960
 You're not a Christian because you got baptized as a baby.

759
00:31:54,960 --> 00:31:57,880
 You're not a Christian because you do right by people

760
00:31:57,880 --> 00:31:59,800
 whenever you walk around the world.

761
00:31:59,800 --> 00:32:01,000
 You're not a Christian because you think

762
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:02,680
 Jesus was actually real.

763
00:32:02,680 --> 00:32:05,360
 You're not a Christian because you think God is true.

764
00:32:05,360 --> 00:32:07,560
 You're not a Christian because you vote Republican.

765
00:32:07,560 --> 00:32:09,840
 You're not a Christian because of any of these reasons.

766
00:32:09,840 --> 00:32:11,840
 The only reason you're a Christian

767
00:32:11,840 --> 00:32:15,160
 is you have come to believe that Jesus Christ

768
00:32:15,160 --> 00:32:17,600
 did in fact live, did in fact die,

769
00:32:17,600 --> 00:32:20,240
 did in fact rise from the dead,

770
00:32:20,240 --> 00:32:21,760
 that you might place your faith in him,

771
00:32:21,760 --> 00:32:23,560
 be forgiven of your sins,

772
00:32:23,560 --> 00:32:25,240
 and you are committed to following him

773
00:32:25,240 --> 00:32:28,080
 as the Lord of your life for the rest of your days.

774
00:32:28,080 --> 00:32:29,680
 That's how you become a Christian.

775
00:32:29,680 --> 00:32:33,180
 (congregation applauding)

776
00:32:33,180 --> 00:32:37,480
 And as I say that, I know some of you are sitting here

777
00:32:37,480 --> 00:32:40,640
 because I have talked to some of you sitting here

778
00:32:40,640 --> 00:32:43,680
 that are actually confused on this point.

779
00:32:43,680 --> 00:32:47,400
 Do not be confused on it any longer.

780
00:32:47,400 --> 00:32:53,760
 Like, this is where the power that backs up the godliness

781
00:32:53,760 --> 00:32:55,200
 that Paul's talking about comes from.

782
00:32:55,200 --> 00:32:56,960
 It doesn't come from you, it comes from him.

783
00:32:56,960 --> 00:32:57,960
 It's nothing you bring to the table.

784
00:32:57,960 --> 00:33:00,840
 It's everything he brings to the table.

785
00:33:00,840 --> 00:33:02,400
 That's why, and I love this,

786
00:33:02,400 --> 00:33:03,680
 that's why some Christians,

787
00:33:03,680 --> 00:33:06,360
 they feel like a force of nature.

788
00:33:06,360 --> 00:33:08,680
 You know what I'm talking about?

789
